# Introduction

Alpha Read was a solution created to help students get proficient at reading comprehension and was developed before Timeback was introduced. Being that the case its internal structures are not perfectly aligned to work with timeback and we had to define some constraints so that it could work with both Timeback and legacy backends. 

The main concepts in Alpha Read are: articles, sections, guiding questions, and the quiz questions.

> **Related Documents:**
> - [COURSE-STRUCTURE-BREAKDOWN.md](./COURSE-STRUCTURE-BREAKDOWN.md) - Understanding the overall hierarchy and how to READ existing content
> - [TIMEBACK_QTI_POWERPATH_GUIDE.md](./TIMEBACK_QTI_POWERPATH_GUIDE.md) - Generic assessment creation (for non-Alpha Read content)

## Articles

Articles are self-contained pieces of text, they contain one or more sections, one or more guiding questions and one or more quiz questions. Articles are represented on Timeback QTI as Assessment Tests, and on OneRoster as Resources.

## Sections

Individual blocks of text inside an article, they may or may not contain an image. Sections are represented in Timeback as QTI Stimuli.

## Guiding Questions

Questions that help the students check their understanding of a section that has just been read. Answering the guiding questions is necessary to unblock the next section of an article. Guiding questions are represented in Timeback as QTI Assessment Items.

## Quiz Questions

Questions that help the students check their understanding of a full article, going over the content of all the sections. Once all quiz questions have been answered, the student's score is recorded. Quiz questions are represented in Timeback as QTI Assessment Items.

# Creating an Alpha Read Article in Timeback QTI

These are the steps to create an Alpha Read article in Timeback QTI:

1. Create all the stimuli needed for the article (remember, each stimulus represents the text of a section).  
2. Create an assessment item for each one of the article questions (guiding and quizzes).  
3. Create an assessment test to group all the different assessment items.

This doc will show the creation of an article with two sections, two guiding questions and a final quiz with two questions as well.

## Stimuli Creation

For each section of the article, we create one stimulus. In the original Alpha Read, each section had its own numeric ID, so we chose to create stimuli IDs following the format `guiding_<section-numeric-id>` where section-numeric-id represents a unique numeric identifier for the section ID. We suggest you get the max article ID from the database \+ 1 since these are unique incremental values and it is necessary to avoid conflicts. We can also create a new endpoint for convenience if needed.   
![][image1]  
Many of the Alpha Read articles contain a first section with an article header that has an image, subtitle and an actual title, followed by a block of text. To achieve this effect, the HTML of the first section has to follow a pattern like the one below using \`data-article-header=true\`:

`<div>`  
   `<div data-article-header="true">`  
       `<figure>`  
           `<img src="https://alpharead-core-knowledge.s3.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/grade_6/history/unit_1/students/images/7_0.png" alt="None"/>`  
           `<figcaption>Sandy dunes of the Sahara desert illustrating a typical arid landscape</figcaption>`  
       `</figure>`  
       `<h1>Exploring Africa's Great Deserts: The Sahara and Kalahari</h1>`  
   `</div>`  
   `<div >`  
       `<p>Deserts are large areas that get very little rain and have few plants. Africa is home to two major deserts: the Sahara and the Kalahari...</p>`  
	`...`  
   `</div>`  
`</div>`

This HTML in the stimulus will result in a section such as this one:  
![][image2]

All requests used in this doc can be found at the end of it.

## Assessment Items Creation

### General Rules

Answers must have identifiers in the format `answer_<answer-numeric-id>` where answer-numeric-id must be a unique number among the answers in this question.

### Guiding Questions

Guiding questions assessment items must have identifiers in the format `guiding_<section-numeric-id>_<question-numeric-id>` where section-numeric-id is the same numeric value used in the creation of the stimulus that represents the section of this guiding question and question-numeric-id is a unique question identifier. They must also have a reference to the section stimulus created previously.  
![][image3]

### Quiz Questions

Quiz questions must have identifiers in the format `quiz_<question-numeric-id>` where question-numeric-id is a unique question identifier (they are supposed to auto increment from the same seed value as the guiding question, so if you had guiding questions as 1, 2 and 3, quiz questions should start from 4). Quiz questions do not need to have references to the stimuli.  
![][image4]

## Assessment Test

Assessment tests must have identifiers in the format `article_<article-numeric-id>` where article-numeric-id is a unique article identifier. These identifiers are sequential numbers and the initial value for a new round of article creation should be requested from AE.   
Aside from the assessment test identifiers, there are some other rules for nested identifiers:

- qti-assessment-section:  
  - sections/guiding questions: the identifiers of assessment sections that will hold guiding questions must follow the pattern `test_<stimuli-id>` where stimuli-id is the Identifier of the stimuli which represents the article section (e.g.  `test_guiding_<section-numeric-id>`). These sections will contain references to the guiding questions for that section. Example identifiers can be found in the raw HTTP requests at the end of this document.  
  - quiz section: the identifier for the quiz section should always be `test_quiz`  
- qti-assessment-item-ref: the identifier references in here should be directly to the question identifiers, guiding or quiz questions. 

![][image5]

## Notes on Multiple Difficulty levels

If it is required that the same assessment test have more than one version of it with varying difficulties, we ask that you create it as if it were a regular brand new assessment test, but that you use the same identifier of the original and append a `_vl` (meaning "version lower”) or `_vh` (meaning “version higher”) to it. For example, if an assessment test's identifier is `article_31482` and you need both a lower difficulty and higher difficulty versions of this test, you would create the new ones with the following identifiers respectively: `article_31482_vl` and `article_31482_vh`.  
Similarly, when creating new versions of assessment items and stimuli, we ask that you also append `_vl` or `_vh` to their identifiers, and use the same identifier of the original question/stimuli as a base.

# Creating OneRoster Course Structure

An Alpha Read article needs a few things to be able to be displayed in the Timeback UI, namely:

- The article must be part of a course.  
- A course must have at least one course component  
- The course component must have one component resource linked to a resource that represents the QTI Article

The order of creation of these resources goes as follows:

1. Course  
2. Course Component  
3. Resource  
4. Component Resource

## Course

![][image6]

## Course Component

![][image7]

## Resource

It’s required that the resource identifier be the same as the article identifier used on QTI (e.g. `article_<article-numeric-id>`) and that the vendor resource id be the numeric portion of the article identifier (e.g. `article-numeric-id`). It’s important to pay attention to other fields as well, such as the metadata which will be used to calculate the XP earned by reading the article.  
In a recent update to Timeback, it is now necessary to specify the lessonType under metadata for new resources. The appropriate lessonType value for Alpha Read articles is `alpha-read-article`  
![][image8]

## Component Resource

Similarly to the resource, we also need the article identifier used here (e.g. `article_<article-numeric-id>`), be that of the article it represents.  
![][image9]
